{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3558139,"name":"Joshua","username":"Joshua1024","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/joshua1024/{size}/255250_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-16T04:37:06.393Z","cooked":"<p>Hello <span class="abbreviation">FRC<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="FIRST Robotics Competition"></template></span> Community,</p>
<p>Our team is integrating the SWYFT Ascend Telescoping Elevator into our robot design, powered by a Kraken X60 motor. While we’ve assembled the mechanical components without alterations to the elevator, we’re encountering challenges in developing effective control code. Our initial code isn’t performing as desired. Specifically, we seek guidance on utilizing the integrated Talon FX controller within the Kraken X60 for smooth bidirectional movement and implementing safety protocols to prevent overextension or unintended movements during operation. Additionally, we are exploring Motion Magic for motion profiling and control. Insights on optimizing Motion Magic parameters for our elevator application would be appreciated, particularly regarding feedforward implementation to counteract gravity and maintain position, considering that motion magic advises against using the kF gain in position control scenarios, and strategies for tuning <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> constants to achieve smooth and precise elevator movements, especially in the context of motion profiling. If your team has experience programming the SWYFT Ascend, Kraken X60, or similar telescoping elevators, particularly using Motion Magic , we would greatly appreciate any insights, code snippets, or resources you could share. Additionally, if there are existing libraries or tools that facilitate this process, please point us in the right direction.</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":4,"updated_at":"2025-03-16T16:42:48.268Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":32,"reads":82,"readers_count":81,"score":176.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":495753,"topic_slug":"seeking-assistance-with-coding-for-swyft-ascend-telescoping-elevator-and-kraken-x60-integration","display_username":"Joshua","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":3,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":63403,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programmer"},"post_url":"/t/seeking-assistance-with-coding-for-swyft-ascend-telescoping-elevator-and-kraken-x60-integration/495753/1","custom_user_title":"Programmer","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3558172,"name":"kuzey","username":"kuzeyatay","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/k/59ef9b/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-03-16T08:45:08.411Z","cooked":"<p>This is a bit confusing. As far as i know you can’t control kraken motors with MAXmotion instead you can use MotionMagic. Which is (i think) the best way of controlling an elevator. In addition to that you can use eighter trapezoid or exponential motion profile if you want to add one. I’d suggest checking out WPIlib’s examples on both of those and for magic motion you can check our <a href="https://github.com/kuzeyatay/2025-Robot-Code/tree/main/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/superstructure/elevator" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">elevator code</a>.  It’s written in IO layers so its a bit confusing. I’d suggest you look at <a href="https://github.com/kuzeyatay/2025-Robot-Code/blob/main/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/superstructure/elevator/Elevator.java" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Elevator.java</a>(we use trapezoid motion profile)  and <a href="https://github.com/kuzeyatay/2025-Robot-Code/blob/main/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/superstructure/elevator/ElevatorIOTalonFX.java" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">ElevatorIOTalonFX.java</a>.</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":4,"updated_at":"2025-03-16T08:46:29.944Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":55,"readers_count":54,"score":16.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":495753,"topic_slug":"seeking-assistance-with-coding-for-swyft-ascend-telescoping-elevator-and-kraken-x60-integration","display_username":"kuzey","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/kuzeyatay/2025-Robot-Code/tree/main/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/superstructure/elevator","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"2025-Robot-Code/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/superstructure/elevator at main · kuzeyatay/2025-Robot-Code · GitHub","clicks":3},{"url":"https://github.com/kuzeyatay/2025-Robot-Code/blob/main/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/superstructure/elevator/Elevator.java","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"2025-Robot-Code/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/superstructure/elevator/Elevator.java at main · kuzeyatay/2025-Robot-Code · GitHub","clicks":2},{"url":"https://github.com/kuzeyatay/2025-Robot-Code/blob/main/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/superstructure/elevator/ElevatorIOTalonFX.java","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"2025-Robot-Code/src/main/java/frc/robot/subsystems/superstructure/elevator/ElevatorIOTalonFX.java at main · kuzeyatay/2025-Robot-Code · GitHub","clicks":1}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":61536,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/seeking-assistance-with-coding-for-swyft-ascend-telescoping-elevator-and-kraken-x60-integration/495753/2","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3558174,"name":"Emre ","username":"DukeEmree","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dukeemree/{size}/251833_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-16T09:17:39.917Z","cooked":"<p>MAXMotion for rev motors. For Kraken and Falcon motors, I think the easiest way is to use MotionMagicExpo. In normal <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span>, there may be synchronization problems in systems with 2 motors. We have tried MotionMagic before. Straight MotionMagic did not work due to some mechanical problems. So we used MotionMagicExpo on recommendation. It is much easier to use and tune. You can change the slope of the graph very easily. 1 motor is leader and other is follower(if you have 2 motors for elevator)<br>
For feedforward and <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> values we applied sysID tests as written in ctre’s documentation.</p>
<p>After finding the maximum and minimum positions of the elevator in terms of rotation, you can put it in the config as in the example. But if you sometimes have problems like the encoder inside the kraken has position error, you may need to close the lower limit and write a command to reset the elevator’s encoder position.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">config.SoftwareLimitSwitch.ForwardSoftLimitEnable = true;
config.SoftwareLimitSwitch.ForwardSoftLimitThreshold = 6;
config.SoftwareLimitSwitch.ReverseSoftLimitEnable = true;
config.SoftwareLimitSwitch.ReverseSoftLimitThreshold = 0;
</code></pre>
